post_text:
The Newfound Schools Administrative Team is working diligently to develop a plan to safely reopen our schools. Committee work is being done by our Administrators, Administrative Assistants, School Nurses, Facilities Director, Technology Director and Teachers.

Our work includes developing plans for Technology, Health Management, Social Emotional Learning, Teaching and Learning, Special Education, Logistics, Professional Development and Facilities.

Through the work of these committees we are confident that we will be prepared to open schools safely.

We are planning to present our reopening plan to the NASD school board on August 3rd. The plan will be distributed to all stakeholders after the school board meeting.

Hello families and friends of the class of 2020!

I apologize for this email being delayed and not being able to get back to everyone who has requested photos. After doing some consideration, I have decided to provide the photographs to everyone for free and not require you to pay for them.

If you would like to send a check as compensation, please feel free to email me at photographybystrikingmoments@gmail.com and I can get you my address or a digital payment account like Venmo. Again, this is not necessary but I have had a few families ask about how to compensate me.

The images can be found at this link,

https://drive.google.com/drive/folders/1iYgsYLdfM8mwM24SDXHUvbf-2dYhAqMc?usp=sharing

They are in order of how the students walked at graduation and I hope to have them all labeled as time goes on. You can simply download directly from the online album and the image is yours.

Congratulations to you and your students for this amazing step in their lives!"

Thank you again!

--
Catherine Roman

Owner of Striking Moments Photography

Today’s 2020 Seniors Salute recognizes Lily Hewitt of Newfound Regional High School. Lily’s Mom, Megan St. Germain, writes, “I would like you to celebrate my daughter Lily. post_text: Last week we received notice that Faith Smith has been awarded the 2020 Walter A. Smith Award that is annually handed out by the NHIAA. The criteria for this prestigous statewide award is for someone that has overcome special circumstances and contributed significantly and positively to New Hampshire athletics. She will be recognized at the 74th NHIAA Annual Meeting in the fall. Congratulations Faith!

post_text:
We are so grateful to our teachers. We see them posting into Google Classroom early in the morning, providing feedback during the day, and replying to students in the evening. While these times are tough for our students, our teachers provide them with structure and care.

While we don't know when socially distancing and remote learning will end, it will. Until then, let this slideshow remind our teachers and our community of the good times we've had together, and the times to come.

Happy teacher appreciation week. Here's to all the great work our teachers do and will continue to do in the future!

Thank you, Mrs. Zick, for all you do for students and staff, especially during these challenging times! Thank you for all the resources and training you are providing others! post_text:
Hello NRHS families!

After two days of hard work, we are ready to supply hard copies of work for students without access to technology, materials for courses that can’t be done entirely online, and Chromebooks to families that signed up.

We have extended hours at the high school for pick up to accommodate our families. You can pick materials up:

Thursday, March 19th from 8:00 am to 7:00 pm
Friday, March 20th from 8:00 am to 2:30 pm

To facilitate social distancing, we are asking familIes to CALL AHEAD before picking up work. This allows us to limit the number of families coming into the building at a time.

If you need to pick up medication from our nurse, you can do so from 1 pm to 7 pm tomorrow and 8 to 2:30 on Friday.

Be well. We are in this together, because #WeAreNewfound!

post_text:
Another one of those cool moments: at 4:15 I walked by the teacher’s lounge. There, Mr. Shelton, Ms. Wiencek, and Mr. Lellos are talking about how to best prepare students for life after high school.

They represent well over 60 years of experience in public education. They also could have left school an hour ago. But here they are, in impassioned discussion, after work, about the important work they do every day. #WeAreNewfound

post_text:
We have a lot to be proud of at NRHS. We often focus on our big accomplishments (like this week’s visit from the US Department of Education!). But it’s often the little things that make a difference in a students’ lives.

Walking the halls today, I found Ms. Presley and Mr. Young giving up their prep periods to provide math help, and Mr. Bonin helping another student with science. They put our students first, saving grading, lesson planning for early in the morning or into the evening. This is the kind of thing our teachers do regularly and is the definition of #WeAreNewfound.

Paul Hoiriis is with Lori Hankard DeVost and Stacy Rabstein Buckley.
March 9 at 3:00 PM ·

What an honor to be visited by the Assistant Secretary of Education for Elementary and Secondary Education. Secretary Frank Brogan paid a visit to Newfound from Washington, DC, to hear what we are doing in NH and at Newfound with Student Voice, Extended Learning, Personalization, and Senior Project. He was impressed with our students and staff and remarked that successful schools organize around students' needs and interests. I couldn't agree more. Proud of who we are and what we are doing!

shared_text:
Newfound Regional First Robotics Team #7913
February 16, 2019 at 6:44 PM ·

Newfound Regional has a FIRST Robotics Competition Team. It was made possible by a generous donation from Freudenberg NOK. For the 2020 season we will be competing in Salem,NH on the weekend of February 27th and in Bedford, NH March 27th.

The team generally meets 5 days a week in the Technology Education room at the high school from 3pm-4:30.

Are you an engineer, machinist, web page designer, or know how to execute a great fundraiser? Perhaps there is another way you'd like to help. Please consider joining us for next year as there is always room to grow and expand to become a greater part of the Newfound community.

Yesterday, Senior Hayleigh spoke about her former teammate who was tragically struck and killed by an intoxicated driver.

To both honor the memory of Mia Stokes and raise awareness of the dangers of impaired driving, we are asking staff, students, and faculty to wear a sports jersey of their choice tomrrow, Friday February 14th.

We will be taking a picture of all participants and sending it to Mia’s family in a show of solidarity and support.

Please consider participating.

To read more about Mia and her twin sister, see: https://www.google.com/amp/s/www.wyff4.com/amp/article/twin-sister-usc-union-teammate-killed-in-crash-2-teammates-injured-by-wrong-way-driver-troopers-say-spartanburg/30824546

post_text: Congratulations! Newfound Regional High, under the direction of coach James LeBaron, has qualified for a wild card spot on the NHPBS high school quiz show, Granite State Challenge.
